1563128201004< /Date>
< rating>
5< /rating>
<text>Not that they need more patronage, as others have mentioned, the waits here can get out of control. But I wanted to throw my two cents here since I've had consistently good experiences and good haircuts here.

My hair is kind of hard to cut. It's curly with a few cowlicks and before I started going to Temescal Alley, it was kinda 50/50 whether I'd like my haircut--regardless of how much I paid.

But then I tried Temescal Alley and I haven't gone anywhere else since.

I've been going here since it was just Nick and Brad in a tiny room with two chairs. As they expanded I was a bit worried that new barbers would mean more variance in my haircuts but I've never gotten a bad haircut here. Which is crazy to me because I've had my hair cut by maybe ten different people there and every time it's good. Sometimes I like my cut more or less but it's always baseline of good.

The barbers are all good natured, nice folks. Their banter and cross talk is usually amusing. And as for the wait--its highly variable. Sometimes there's no wait at all. Other times you come in and the waitlist is full for the entire day.

If you like the barbers but need a scheduled appointment, try Al's Barbershop in Alameda. It's the same folks but appointment-only.</text>< Pictures>

< Review>
Been coming here for almost two years now and refuse to go anywhere else. These guys and gals know how to give a great haircut/beard trim. First come first serve and each barber has their own style, yet I've never left unsatisfied despite the occasional +hour wait. Relaxed atmosphere with hilarious banter. If you appreciate a great trim you owe it to yourself to visit Temescal Alley Barber Shop.< /Review>

<username>Joshua Engberg< /username><time>1531875931146<//time><Rate>5<//Rate><Review>First time coming here today, the price was $30 and I came in on a Tuesday afternoon at 1:30pm. I came in and was greeted and put my name on the chalkboard and was given a 90min wait time. Of course I wish it was shorter but I was prepared as there is plenty to occupy your time nearby, like a afternoon glass of wine with my wife at Dona Tomas at the end of the alley. < text>
Came here for the first time not too long ago. I really liked my haircut, but like others have probably mention the wait here is INSANE. I came and hour before the shop opened and still had to wait 45 minutes to hour. Thankfully there's Cro next door, where you can grab a coffee and pastry as you wait. The guys here are as hipster as hipster get but they know what they are doing. They are no frills and get right down to business. I'm use to going to salons and having long conversations with the stylist but not here. You'll come in, get your hair cut, and leave. I don't think I would come any later than right when they open, however these guys give a good haircut.< /text>

< user_name>
David Hidalgo< /user_name>
< rate>
5</rate>
< review>
I needed a trailer to haul my golf cart behind my motorhome. I looked at several different options and almost bought a swivel tote trailer but then  saw the Kendon Trailer website and stand up utility trailers.  After further research and comparisons, I decided on the Kendon Stand up Utility Trailer.

I called, spoke to Javier and placed an order for one. Took a couple of months to get, and a little pricey, but it is well worth the wait and and money spent.  It is  a beautiful very high quality and sturdy  trailer. It is somewhat heavy and I need help standing it up, but it is nice that I can store it inside my garage up against the wall. Everywhere I take it, I get many compliments and inquiry's about it. I have been very pleased with my trailer and customer service from Kendon Trailers! I highly recommend their trailers and lifts!<//review>
< Date>
1630356444920</Date>

<Rating>5<//Rating><Text>I‚Äôm selling my 2012 Kendon Dual SLR after 10 years because I‚Äôm no longer traveling with my bike. This is my second Kendon trailer. Both have performed exceptionally well - I could never tell it was behind me and handling was awesome when in the rain. <user_id>108136932894199595817< /user_id>< resp>
{'time': 1538587251976, 'text': "Thomas, thanks so much for the feedback!  We got it and we'll work on making additional improvements."}</resp>
<GmapID>0x80dcd6c9418302c7:0xd9f5d38c9b538123<//GmapID>< user_name>
Thomas Burns<//user_name>
< text>
Excellent trailer; best in class. This is the second Kendon I have owned.

A couple suggestions for the Kendon design team to consider for future refinements (which would kick my rating to a 5):
1. The factory added a third rail to my Kendon dirt bike stand-up and found that the bolts used on the new rail were different than the other two; requiring a different wrench (Std vs metric) to adjust the wheel chock.
2. A custom expensive tongue stand is required on the new trailer design. Suggest going back to the inexpensive leveler design and providing a simple mounting plate so the trailer is not scratched up. I added a rubber door stop to the main frame to prevent scratches and rust.
3.  The lugs to remove the spare tire are a different size than the lugs to remove a tire! This is very odd; should be the same size.
4. The spare tire ground clearance is horrible; tire easily bottoms out on the road. Suggest providing mounts on the top side of the deck. This is better than designing the trailer for an underside mount which could damage the tire.

Even with these flaws, still best in class.</text>
< Date>
1538513391023<//Date>
< pictures>
None<//pictures>
<rating>4< /rating></record></dataset><record>
<user_name>Edward Basham</user_name><date>1522605397786</date>< user_id>
105941178140073631211<//user_id>
<text>I ordered a single standup trailer during Kendon's Black Friday promotion this past fall (2017). Communication with Kendon was great and they even offered me a two-tone paint scheme at no extra charge. Generally the trailer I received was very well constructed, but I do have some criticisms and that's why I'm only giving them 4 stars. The problems I have with my trailer are as follow:

1) Kendon's standard trailers come with incandescent tail/turn/break lights. In this day and age, and especially at this price point, LEDs should be standard.  There's really no excuse for this and I replaced the lights immediately.

2) A full-size spare tire (exact size as tires on the trailer) will not fit where the spare tire bracket is welded to the underside of the trailer because the frame tubes on either side are too close together. Now I was probably going to carry the spare in the back of my truck anyway, but the option would be nice and why weld something on that can't be used?

3) The wheel chock is not very effective.  I have a Condor chock that holds either of my bikes upright very well, but the chock on the Kendon trailer can't be trusted to hold my 2015 Kawasaki Versys for even a moment while I tie it down.  The bike has to rest on its kickstand otherwise it will fall over.  Maybe I'm just spoiled by the Condor chock but I think Kendon could learn something from Condor's design.

4) Don't expect to stand the trailer up and roll it into a standard height garage, it's too tall. You have to push the trailer inside clear of the door frame and then lift it upright where you have more clearance.  I don't think this is a design flaw, but Kendon should make this clear as some might expect that you could stand it up in your driveway and just push it in. Obviously if you have an RV door there's no problem.

These trailers are good, but they could be great with a couple of tweaks.  For what I paid, I expected great.<//text>< resp>
None</resp>

Standing it on it's end as advertised is a challenge,  This suckers heavy.  But we removed the ramps and hitch (easy) and we could manage it.  Build out was amazing.  It's a very well built.  The guys that helped me put it together were airline mechanics and they were impressed.  The only reason I didn't give this trailer 5 stars is because it is very hard to stand up on it's end for storage, but that being said it has to be strong (heavy) to hold the weight of a 1200 pound trike.< /Review>

<review>First, I decided to Google search for folding motorcycle trailer models. Although, more expensive, the Kendon Dual ride up trailer appeared to be the best design. Next step was to see the actual trailer in use at a motorcycle ride event. Convinced by what I observed, you can very easily ride on and off the trailer without assistance, I called Kendon directly. The Kendon representative, Elliott, arranged for my purchase of a demo Dual Ride up trailer. It was delivered to a freight terminal on a short of pallet. <Rate>4<//Rate>< Review>
The concept of a folding motorcycle trailer (in my case a trike trailer)  is excellent.  It works well for the cramped garage space that I store it in.  I think the finished product is lacking in 2 important details however: (1) there are no owners manual directions on how to properly store the ramps under the trailer when it is in use.  When I did call the Company, the suggested storage solution and the company supplied pins to do so were not very satisfactory; and (2) the trailer rides too low and the suspension setup that the trailer comes with (torsion bar) is not ride height adjustable like Chrysler Corporation models up to the '90's that used the same system were.  It is very easy to scrape the trailer bottom when going into a driveway or driving on a gravel/dirt road that has a high center.  I really liked the salesperson that helped me (both pre and post sale), though.< /Review>

<Pics>None< /Pics>< text>
I was the winner of the 25th Anniversary Logo contest. I won the BB107 Single Bike Trailer which was quite a coincidence because I had just sold my 2 bike SRL trailer with plans to buy a Single Bike Trailer. Working with Steven Adams from Kendon Trailers, I arranged to upgrade the trailer I had won to the one I really wanted, the BB107RULE (Limited Edition) by paying the difference of the two trailers (plus I bought a couple of extras). Since the factory was only 300 miles away from me I decided to drive down to LA and pick it up. The only complication was the fact that they are only open during the week so it made scheduling the trip a little more difficult. With Steven's help we coordinated the pick-up for May 13th and I was there at 9am to pick it up. I had the twin utility boxes mounted on the trailer by the guy's at Kendon and when Steven took me back to the area where the trailers are built and I got my first look at my trailer I was totally stunned at how beautiful it was (pictures do not do it justice). The bright orange frame with gloss black rails, fenders, and boxes and the polished diamond plate flooring and lid's of the utility boxes made it look like a true work of art. I made a couple of stops on my way home that day and someone would always come up to me asking what that was behind my car. All n all it was a great experience working with the guy's and girl who work at Kendon Trailers (I'm sorry, I forgot the dog also) and although I have not towed my bike anywhere on the trailer yet I look forward to doing so. The down side is like buying a new car. You dread that first scratch or mud puddle you have to drive through but it is inevitable. Thank you so much Steven and Kendon Trailers for a job well done.< /text>

110895759511436893254< /user>
<Text>I've had my 2-Up bike trailer for maybe 14 years now. Lots of days and thousands of miles of trailing with 2 or 1 bike. Or one rail moved (and braced) into a center position.
All and all a great trailer. It's too heavy now for my old body to stand up with spare attached below. I may switch to a single.

Though the trailer's low profile is great, I've never been jazzed about the narrow 4-tube loading ramp. It can be spooky loading a full dress bike w/no where to put one foot down (depending on right or left side) as you motor up.

I attached traction adhesive to the center 2 tubes. Loading in the rain can be squirrelly.  I do a 4 point tie-down but occasional a bike's back end shifts across the slick sheet metal.
The stand-up wheel castors have been near terrible. Not heavy duty enough for me. Only good on the hardest-smoothest of surfaces. I have replaced them twice over the years and they are broken again.

I have had to have 3 deck support brackets re-welded under the plating. Too many pot holes and thousands of miles of abuse.

Florida State Trooper - "mistakenly" told me the safety cable MUST be a chain not a wire cable. And she won't let me drive off.   _itch.

All and all probably the best open bike trailer out there... imo</Text>< Response>
None< /Response>

<text>Great trailer, agree with everyone, except... with Yamaha Royal Star Venture motorcycle used trailer twice:
1) Tie down rings located on axle has wiring for lights going through it.  On most bikes it may be O.K. but with an RSV, or HD (length) it's DANGEROUS - strap hook almost cut through wiring.  Sent email - told to use soft strap to get behind wiring.  No response on alternate design recommendation.

2) On a 600-mile trip had spare tire fell off while on a I-10 Mississippi Bridge - no pull-over lane, couldn't stop, spare caught under trailer caused serious damage to frame.  Checked spare tire about halfway point, seemed O.K.  Realized bumpy roads in MS and LA shook things loose - FAST.  Didn't realize danger until too late.  After $300 repairs drilled hole through spare tire lug-bolts and installed two I/4" linch pins with self-locking ring to prevent lug-nuts from completely slipping off.  Sent email to Kendon, not looking for remedy but to inform of danger and recommend solution - no response.

I would recommend this trailer to anyone - after rewiring the lights to avoid the axle tie-down ring and drilling holes through spare tire lug-bolts and installing a linch pin.</text>< date>
1466952551841<//date>

These guys know what they are doing/selling. Just bought Tribe bicep leash. Tribe is their brand. High quality leash designed/built with bodyboarder in mind/heart. I tried cheaper (50%) leash with great reviews from amazon but returned it immediately after receiving due to major design flaws. Tribe leash is superior in design and quality: allows buckling up with one hand and attaches through the ring giving more flexibility. Great product and Co! Worth every penny. P.S. I was not paid to write this review.<//review>

< review>
Horrible/non existant customer service on behalf of two particular people in the store. My bf and I came into walmart an hour before closing and were waiting around the jewelry department asking the other associates who were nearby to call for their coworker who had access to some of the rings I wanted to try on (btw both the manager and the associate in charge of that department were called 5 different times. Pretty excessive and ridiculous if you ask me). Unfortunately we waited over 25min (10 when we first got to the department and another 15 or so after waiting around for someone to show up) for either Sara the manager and/or Claire the associate assigned to that department. I understand that alot of employees and managers wanna wrap things up because it is nearing the end of closing up for the night, but that is no excuse for neglecting your job duties because you are still on the clock until 11pm exactly. Not 10-10:45pm. And I've never heard of a 25 min break before closing so no one can use that as excuse either. So long story short we left unsatisfied and quite frankly annoyed because it was obvious that we were being ignored by those two in particular who clearly did not feel like fulfilling their job duties until the very end of their shift. Everyone else who was either walking by or was in a nearby department was very friendly and willing to help and we definitely appreciated it.<//review>

< text>
This is honestly the best Walmart I've ever been to, or at least that I can remember. I live in the Bay Area in Oakland and the Walmarts there are horrible, absolutely horrible! Long lines, messy stores, they don't restock the shelves, no variety of items, etc, etc. But, this Walmart is clean, the items on the shelves look perfectly placed (like the shelves stay untouched), they have great variety, the atmosphere is open and peaceful.... Literally, I'm looking around and every aisle looks neat and organized. It's like a Target in a nice neighborhood. :) Even there's staff walking around helping people... and they're polite and friendly. The workers at Bay Area stores are young people with bad attitudes and little professionalism. I'm sure people around here are complaining because they have no idea how good they have it. I've lived in Oakland, Seattle, Kansas City, Chicago, and been many other places. Most Walmarts I've been to are an embarrassment to the company. Walmart Corporate should force those other store managers to visit this Walmart and learn from whoever manages this store. I feel so frustrated with Walmart in general, so this place is a breath of fresh air! Well done Buena Park Walmart!< /text>
